subSubSection.paragraph:
Head—
dichoptic with dark red eyes and nudiocular area developed (
Fig. 2
). Frons, clypeus and occiput pruinose with scattered adpressed yellow hairs, denser on eye margin and occiput. Some yellow hairs on posterior margin of eye. Mouthparts light to dark brown. Antenna with scape and pedicel yellowish brown, remainder black. Cibarium with well sclerotised cornuae and central trough unarmed and unsclerotised (
Fig. 17
).

Abdomen—
tergite I brown, brass coloured hairs on basal fringe; tergite II with anterior half brown and posterior half black, faintly pruinose; tergite III black, faintly pruinose; tergites IV–IX shiny black with scattered yellow hairs. Tergal plates developed. Sternites dirty white; genitalia dark brown to black. Eighth sternite sclerotised with 1+1 groups of about 12 setae; gonapophyses broadly subtriangular, lobed distally, apparently glabrous and sclerotised on inner margins and apical half of posterior margin (
Fig. 107
). Cercus hemispherical, covered with distinct, long, brown setae; paraproct subrectangular with ventral subtriangular extension about one and a half times longer than cercus, highly setose (
Fig. 122
). Genital fork with slender sclerotised stem, anterior processes of posterior arms broadly triangular and sclerotised, posterior processes undeveloped (
Fig. 138
). Spermatheca oval with smooth texture and spicules on inner surface of variable size, grouped in threes in basal half and scattered in distal half; area of insertion of spermathecal duct membranous.

Thorax—
scutum black with golden and silvery, recumbent setae. Scutal pattern varies with light inci- dence: with anterior light source thorax pruinose on anterior third, except 1+1 lateral, velvet black areas on anterior margin (
Fig. 154
); humeri and lateral margins black. With light source posterior to specimen thorax black (
Fig. 155
) [sometimes faintly pruinose areas can be seen in central area on anterior third]; humeri and lateral margin weakly pruinose [best seen when specimens are tilted laterally]. Scutellum brown with golden, recumbent hairs and long, erect, dark brown setae. Postnotum dark brown to black with silvery grey pruinosity. Wing setation as in female. Leg coloration as in female.

Abdomen—
tergites black, basal fringe with long, brown hairs. Silver pruinose ornamentation as follows: anterolateral margin of tergite II, and lateral margin of tergites V–VIII [best seen when specimens viewed laterally]. Tergal plates developed; genitalia black. Gonocoxite subrectangular, slightly wider than long; gonostyle trapezoidal, shorter than gonocoxite and with small apical spine; gonocoxite and gonostyle covered with long setae (
Fig. 181
). Ventral plate sclerotised, narrow and convex dorsally, with main body having distal end broadly pointed; main body of ventral plate covered by numerous spiniform setae concentrated along mid line (
Fig. 195
). Median sclerite pear-shaped with apical incision (
Fig. 207
). Paramere with well developed and sclerotised basal process and several long spines apically (
Fig. 220
).
